params.proof: merkle proof that the user is whitelisted.

params.maxResultingDebt: in WETH terms. While it is unlikely that the exchange rate changes from when a transaction is submitted versus when it is executed, it is still possible so we want to allow for a bound here, even though it doesn't pose the same level of threat as slippage.

flashswapDeleverage(uint256,uint256,uint.details: The two function parameters must be chosen carefully. If `maxCollateralToRemove` were higher then `debtToRemove`, it would theoretically be possible TODO: to do what?

params.maxResultingAdditionalDebt: in terms of WETH. How much debt to add to the position in the vault.
params.resultingAdditionalCollateral: in terms of swEth. How much collateral to add to the position in the vault.
params.sqrtPriceLimitX96: for the swap. Recommended value is the current exchange rate to ensure the swap never costs more than a direct mint would.

receiveFlashLoan(address[],uint256[],uin.details: This function is intended to never be called directly. It should only be called by the Balancer VAULT during a flashloan initiated by this contract. This callback logic only handles the creation of leverage positions by minting. Since not all tokens have withdrawable liquidity via the LST protocol directly, deleverage through the protocol will need to be implemented in the inheriting contract.

params.userData: arbitrary data passed from initiator of flash loan

uniswapV3SwapCallback(int256,int256,byte.details: From the perspective of the pool i.e. Negative amount means pool is sending. This function is intended to never be called directly. It should only be called by the Uniswap pool during a swap initiated by this contract. One thing to note from a security perspective is that the pool only calls the callback on `msg.sender`. So a theoretical attacker cannot call this function by directing where to call the callback.
